To use the `plot` function in MATLAB, you can follow these steps with an example code snippet. This example demonstrates how to plot the function \( y = \sin(x) \) from \( x = -\pi \) to \( \pi \).

### Example MATLAB Code

```matlab
% Define the range of x values from -pi to pi
x = linspace(-pi, pi, 100);

% Calculate the corresponding y values
y = sin(x);

% Plot the function
figure;
plot(x, y);

% Add labels and title
xlabel('x');
ylabel('y');
title('Plot of y = sin(x) from -\pi to \pi');

% Optionally, add grid lines for better readability
grid on;
```

### Code Snippet Showing Function Usage

```matlab
% Usage of plot function
plot(x, y);
```

This code snippet shows how to use the `plot` function to create a 2D line plot of \( y = \sin(x) \) over the specified range of \( x \). The `plot` function takes two arguments: the x-values and the corresponding y-values. The additional commands `xlabel`, `ylabel`, and `title` are used to label the axes and add a title to the plot, while `grid on` adds grid lines for better readability.
